title: how to use launch control and burnout mode in the c8 corvette (w
body: Launch control isn't new, and it isn't new to the Corvette, but with an all-new eight-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission and electronic shifter in the
C8 Corvette
, using it is now just a little different. Plus, there's a new burnout mode for warming your tires before the race.

Getting the perfect launch is all about getting the vehicle moving in the most effective manner, but it doesn't always mean using all the traction. After testing thousands upon thousands of cars, we find it often depends on both the car and the tires it's wearing. Some cars can just squat and go, but others need a little bit of wheel spin—which by definition isn't using all of the tire's available traction—to prevent the engine from bogging. The trade-off there is what time you lose with wheel spin is less than you'd lose by bogging. With advanced launch control systems, though, you don't even have to think about it.

It used to be a good driver could consistently beat the launch control, but these days a good computer can monitor the powertrain and wheels so precisely and respond so quickly a human just can't do any better. With its new weight balance and latest Performance Traction Management (PTM) software, the C8 Corvette is one of those cars. Using it is slightly more difficult than some sports cars, but you'll recognize the procedure from past Corvettes.

The first step is to put the car in Drive and select Track mode, then double-tap the ESC Off button just ahead of the mode selector knob. This will bring up the PTM menu on the instrument cluster and allow you to select which program you want with the mode selector knob. The programs are familiar—Wet, Dry, Sport I, Sport II, and Race—and the computer safety net shrinks as you go through them. It doesn't matter which you pick, Launch Control works in all of them and will give the best launch regardless.

Once you've selected a PTM mode, it's as easy as standing on the brake with your left foot, flooring the gas with your right foot, and lifting off the brake after the revs settle at 3,500. Then, hang on and steer as the car does its thing.
As any racer knows, if you want the best grip whether for launching or cornering, you have to warm your tires.
Chevy

's got a mode for that, unofficially named "burnout mode." It's even easier to use than Launch Control because you don't need to get into PTM modes and all that. Just put the car in drive, stand on the brake, pull both steering wheel paddles to temporarily open the clutches, floor the throttle, and release the paddles when you're ready to go. The computer will do a carefully controlled clutch dump and will let the tires spin rather than trying to get the perfect launch. When you're done, just lift off the throttle.

title: plans dropped for $23 million titusville sports arena
body: A proposal to build a $23 million indoor sports arena and hotel complex in Titusville has fallen through.
The project would have been a public/private partnership partially funded with $7 million from Brevard County's Tourist Development Tax on hotel rooms and other short-term rentals.

Although the Brevard County Commission and the county's Tourist Development Council approved the $7 million in funding in 2017, no tourist tax money actually went to the project because it never got off the ground.

The arena would have been used for basketball and volleyball tournaments, as well as for other sports tournaments and competitions, including wrestling, cheerleading and dance. It also could have been used as a venue for trade shows, conferences, entertainment events and social events.
Help support our local journalism

Space Coast Office of Tourism Executive Director Peter Cranis said a private company that had been considering developing the project found that it was not economically viable and decided against moving forward. That company, Delaware North, had been looking into expanding its local presence, as it operates the Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex for NASA.

Brevard County Commissioner Rita Pritchett — whose commission district includes Titusville — said there are no other developers interested in pursuing the project. But she hopes another tourism economic development project will materialized for the Titusville area in the future.
High-end Cocoa Beach resort could be 'game changer' for county, bring big business
Sports events, ranging from half-marathons to girls' softball, awarded tourist tax grants

Cranis told members of the Tourist Development Council's Capital Facilities Committee at their meeting this month that, with the Titusville sports arena off the table, the money targeted for that project could be redirected to other tourism-related capital projects.

But Cranis emphasized that doesn't mean the Office of Tourism now has $7 million to spend on other projects, since about $5 million of that amount likely would have been financed if the project went forward.

The 5% Tourist Development Tax raised about $16 million in the budget year that ended Sept. 30. Tourism-related capital projects are designated to receive the equivalent of 14% of the money generated by the tax.

Troy Post, executive director of the North Brevard Economic Development Zone, which submitted the original project proposal, said Delaware North was one of several entities he had pitched the idea for the arena/hotel project.

In addition to a downtown Titusville site, Post said locations he had been looking at were the Titusville Mall (formerly known as the Searstown Mall), as well as the former stand-alone site of the U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame, which has moved to the KSC Visitor Complex.
"There does not appear to be a potential partner out there," Post said. "We think there is still a need for such a facility. But we're going to take a step back."
Cranis, Post and Pritchett said they were not provided details of Delaware North's findings.

But an earlier study by RevPar International Inc., a hospitality advisory and asset management company, found that an arena/hotel project in downtown Titusville could be economically viable; could spur tourism and economic development in the Titusville area; and could "create a hub of activity in downtown Titusville."

RevPar studied the concept at the request of the North Brevard Economic Development Zone board. The 13-acre site studied for arena/hotel complex was near U.S. 1 and Garden Street in downtown Titusville.
RevPar found that the sports arena would lose money, but the hotel would make more money than the arena would lose.

In its first year of operation, the hotel would have a profit of $942,000 and the arena would have a loss of $616,950, RevPar estimated. In its fifth year of operation, the hotel would have an annual profit of $1.39 million, and the arena would have an annual loss of $187,850.
RevPar recommended that the arena be 75,000 square feet so it could accommodate six basketball courts or 12 volleyball courts for tournament play.

The study said that, within five years, the facility could have been used 100 days a year, for 18 national- and state-level tournaments plus 24 regional- and local-level tournaments. Those events would draw 55,900 people and generate 58,000 nights of hotel room rentals.

RevPar recommended a 100-room, all-suite hotel that had a national brand and was in the upper-midscale to upscale category be located adjacent to the arena. It said such a hotel could achieve an occupancy rate of 74% in five years, with an average room price of $124 a day.

Along with the sports arena project, four other tourist-tax-funded capital projects were approved in 2017 by the County Commission in a 4-1 vote, with Commissioner John Tobia opposed. The projects were recommended by the advisory Tourist Development Council and its Capital Facilities Committee.
Three have been completed:
• The tourist tax provided $5 million to help convert seven natural-grass sports fields at Viera Regional Park to AstroTurf. These fields are used for soccer, football and lacrosse.
• $500,000 for construction of a Keepers Cottage Museum at the Cape Canaveral Lighthouse.

• $199,495 for upgrades to the Oars & Paddles Park and pier area in Indian Harbour Beach. The project includes an additional pier; repairs to the existing pier; installation of pilings, gangways and railings; and an additional 60 parking spaces to accommodate paddlers.

The other allocation in 2017 was $1.7 million to help fund an expansion of the Palm Bay Nature Center and Campground at Fred Poppe Regional Park. That project is on hold as the city seeks additional sources of funding for the project.

In 2018, the county approved a $500,000 allocation from the tourist tax for exhibits at the Merritt Island National Wildlife Refuge's Community Conservation Education Center, as part of an expansion of that facility. Cranis said that project is nearing completion.
FLORIDA TODAY.
@bydaveberman

title: nyc caves and authorizes wtc benefits for 9
body: After months of claiming a retired FDNY firefighter’s cancer was linked to excessive drinking, and not his time at Ground Zero, the city finally agreed to provide the sickened smokeater with a full 9/11 disability pension, the Daily News has learned.
The decision comes roughly one month after former firefighter Joe Daly’s plight was outlined in an exclusive story in the Daily News — and after a court ordered the city to stop stalling.
The city confirmed on Wednesday that it will follow the court order and give Daly his full disability pension.
Daly’s wife Dana was happy with the outcome, although she said the approval could have happened much sooner.
“The city did the right thing for one of its members (but) it took a long time,” Dana Daly told The News on Thursday.
Daly retired from Engine 218 in Bushwick, Brooklyn in 2004. Five years later, he was diagnosed with several cancers that have since ravaged his bladder, liver and colon.

Before The News’ story came out, the city had considered appealing a court order demanding it provide Daly with a full disability pension, even though doctors inextricably linked the sicknesses to his time breathing in the toxins at Ground Zero following the terror attacks. He had already received hundreds of thousands of dollars from the federal 9/11 Victim Compensation Fund to pay for doctor visits and medications.
Yet the city Fire Pension Fund had determined that Daly’s cancers didn’t stem from Ground Zero, but from chronic drinking — even though Daly was never labeled an alcoholic.

In court papers shared with The News, the city said that Daly’s liver cancer was “due to (accumulation of fluid in the abdomen) and abdominal distention, which were the result of alcoholic liver disease” and that the firefighter had suffered cirrhosis of the liver in the past.
Daly sued to get a full disability pension. The extra money would go a long way toward paying the mounting bills he’s accumulated during his cancer fight, his family said.

On Sept. 3, Supreme Court Justice Katherine Levine ordered the city to give Daly a full, tax-free disability pension, claiming that the FDNY Medical Board’s denial “lacked a rational basis and was arbitrary and capricious because (they) undiscerningly accepted the Medical Board’s recommendation, which was based on cherry-picked evidence."
But the city never moved forward, claiming they were “reviewing the court’s ruling.”
“We defended the expert medical board’s decision as legally correct,” a Law Department spokesman said at the time.
Daly’s attorney Jeffrey Goldberg said he was “pleased that the long ordeal is finally over" and the retired firefighter can get some peace of mind.

“Unfortunately, Firefighter Daly suffers every day from WTC-related cancers, but is relieved that his sacrifice was acknowledged by FDNY and that his family’s financial well-being is protected in the future,” Goldberg said.

title: hbo's '24
body: Head coach Herm Edwards is understandably the main focus of HBO's “24/7 College Football: Arizona State Sun Devils.”

How could he not be? A successful professional coach who returns to coach a college team after 10 years talking about football on TV — which means he’s really good at talking on TV, which is a dream come true for a documentarian?
So yes, there’s a lot of Edwards.
But there needs to be more of Frank Darby.

Darby, a junior wide receiver, pops up in the one-hour show from time to time like a scene-stealing supporting actor, and he does what all great actors do: leaves us wanting more. Outspoken, loud, occasionally a little profane and endlessly enthusiastic, he’s a joy to watch. Whether he’s a joy to have a locker next to, who knows? But he lights up “24/7” every time he appears on the screen.

The format of the show, which features a different team each week, is simple. HBO cameras spend a week at a college as it prepares and then plays in a game. We see it day by day. If you’ve ever wondered just what a team does when its players aren’t on the field on game day, “24/7” gives you some idea.

But just some. It’s so overwhelmingly positive as to be almost Pollyanna-ish in its portrayal of the student athlete preparing for battle. The production values are impeccable. The athletic facilities are amazing. Liev Schreiber narrates in dramatic fashion, because if you hire Liev Schreiber that’s what you’re paying him for. If this was all you knew of ASU you might think it was Harvard with a team that never lost a game.
It may be the ultimate recruiting tool.
It helps that the game the Sun Devils were preparing for — and which we see bits and pieces of during the show — turned out to be a thriller,
a 38-34 win over Washington State
(the subject of “24/7” on Wednesday, Oct. 23). Edwards preaches preparation and responsibility throughout the week; all that would ring a little hollow if it hadn’t resulted in a win.
How ASU football plans to use early enrollment to get ahead
subscribe to azcentral.com.
Although Edwards is a pretty magnetic presence, no matter the outcome. “I’ve been betting on me my whole life,” he says, and you definitely come away thinking that sounds like a pretty good wager.

We also see freshman quarterback Jayden Daniels, not just on the field during practice, but also walking across University Drive in Tempe, on his way to class to turn in a rough draft of an English paper. That leads to a quick bit on Kyle Williams, a receiver majoring in biomedical engineering
who has worked as a research intern for the Mayo Clinic
; he got interested in medicine after a shoulder injury.

There’s also a segment on Pat Tillman, the ASU great who walked away from the Arizona Cardinals to join the Army after 9/11 and was killed. We see his statue, Schreiber relates his story and then we hear from Tommy Hudson, a tight end inspired by Tillman. When Hudson’s done with football, he, too will join the military, he says.

If that sounds like a lot of story packed into a little time, it is. Too much so, in fact. We get appetizers when each nugget offers enough interesting fodder for a full meal. “24/7” has to squeeze all this, along with regular check-ins with Edwards and his staff, into an hour, and still have time to show highlights from the game.
Nevertheless, if you’re a die-hard ASU fan, it’s required viewing — you’re going to see and hear exactly what you want to.
bill.goodykoontz@arizonarepublic.com
facebook.com/GoodyOnFilm
@goodyk
HBO's '24/7 College Football' makes stars out of ASU and Herm Edwards

title: chef rick araujo wins chopped!
body: Rick Araujo is the executive chef who won the coveted "Golden Cleaver" Award at Chopped!/Worcester 2019, the fundraiser for Jeremiah's Inn held last week at Maironis Park Banquet Hall in Shrewsbury.

Araujo, who represented Lettuce Be Local in Sterling (Central Mass Food Hub), and three other chefs proved their culinary expertise in creating an appetizer and entrée using ingredients commonly found in food pantries. When the mystery bags were opened the chefs discovered they had to use unsalted matzos, black beans, whole water chestnuts and canned salmon for the appetizer. For the entrée, chefs were given Idahoan Classic Mashed with Butter & Cream potatoes, sliced pears, Trappist Hot Pepper Jelly and clam juice. Chefs were allowed to incorporate other items, such as produce, sauces, etc.

The chefs originally had 30 minutes to prepare both dishes, but several minutes into cooking they were handed a pork chop (protein) and given 10 more minutes on the clock. The pork chop was one of those oops moments, and the chefs took it in stride, commenting that the same thing can and does happen in restaurant kitchens.

Bill Bourbeau, executive chef/GM of The Boynton Restaurant & Spirits in Worcester, was runner-up, followed by Chris Bairos, executive chef representing Broth in Worcester, and Lauren Fiores, a local chef who previously worked at Worcester Country Club and first-time culinary competitor.

Araujo, Bourbeau and Bairos have previously won other culinary awards, with Bourbeau voted the 2019 Iron Chef at Worcester's Best Chef competition and Araujo, a Judges' Choice winner at the 2019 WBC competition.

Janelle L. Wilson, executive director at Jeremiah's Inn, said this year's Chopped event was so successful it topped ticket sales from the past two years. All the proceeds of the event directly support programming, she said.

"What makes Chopped!/Worcester so special is the continued support year after year of those involved — chefs from the first years who have returned to serve as judges and emcee's, provide hors d'oeuvres, or purchase tickets and attend the event," said Wilson. "Executive chefs Mike Arrastia and Jay Powell kept us entertained throughout the evening, and the band members from Belit donated their time to perform live for the past three years. It truly 'takes a village' to help our neighbors who are less fortunate or struggling from substance use disorders and this event is a wonderful example of how we all can come together to make a difference."

According to Wilson, 30 percent of Worcester's children live in a household that struggles to meet their basic food needs. Jeremiah's Inn Nutrition Center provides food to more than 8,000 individuals each year. Thirty percent of the inn's clients are under the age of 18 and another 30 percent are 65 or older. Residential recovery services are provided to more than 100 men each year. Learn more about Jeremiah's Inn's services at
www.jeremiahsinn.com

Wilson said Chopped! wouldn't have happened without sponsors such as Fallon Health, Reliant Medical Group, Savers Bank, Smith, Sullivan & Brown, PC, William F. Lynch, LEI Corporation, Teamsters Local 170, Bay State Savings Bank, Masterman's, O'Connor Maloney & Co, M3 Innovations Inc., Angel Guard Products Inc., HeadShop Hair Factory and Cherie's Soul Creations.
Congrats to Araujo and competing chefs.

slender man stabbing victim's interview part of new '20
body: The Slender Man stabbing case from Waukesha returns to national television Friday when ABC's "20/20" presents an exclusive interview with Payton Leutner, who was only 12 when her two friends tried to fatally stab her in 2014.
Leutner, now 17, was left for dead with 19 stab wounds before she crawled from some woods at a park to a trail where she was found by a passing bicyclist.

Morgan Geyser and Anissa Weier, also 12 at the time, were arrested the same day and told police in recorded interviews that they believed they had to kill Leutner to avoid the wrath of Slender Man, an internet bogeyman they said would kill them or their families if they didn't. They were charged as adults with attempted first-degree intentional homicide.

Each is now committed to state mental health supervision after being found not guilty by reason of mental disease or defect, Geyser for 40 years and Weier for 25, and both reside at a secure state hospital.

Leutner's parents struck an exclusive deal with "20/20" early on; the show first reported extensively on the case as Payton was ready to return to school for seventh grade, after spending the summer recovering from her injuries and subsequent surgeries from the May 2014 attack. The case was the subject of at least two more episodes of "20/20" as it played out.
Her parents spoke on camera with host David Muir, but never did any other interviews.

According to ABC, Friday's two-hour episode, titled "The Wicked," will feature updated talks with Joe and Stacie Leutner, as well as interviews with the detectives who first interrogated Geyser and Weier, a prosecutor, a defense attorney, a reporter, Geyser and Weier's mothers, and doctors who evaluated the defendants.

title: winston salem
body: The Winston-Salem/Forsyth County Schools Board of Education voted against requiring students to take an African American history course before graduating high school. The school board passed unanimously an alternative proposal by District Superintendent Angela Hairston. The motion passed Tuesday adds more ethnic classes to their curriculum.

Under the proposal, high school students across the district would be required to pass one of the following courses to graduate: African American Studies, Latin American Studies, American Indian Studies or Ethnic Literature.
Hairston, along with others, are concerned that another mandatory course could negatively impact graduation rates.
School leaders believe students would benefit from increased access to multicultural experiences, improve their appreciation for different cultures and lessen xenophobic behaviors and attitudes.
About 20 people made passionate comments during the public comment section of the meeting Tuesday.
School leaders said the conversation about adding an African American course has been a matter of discussion for about three years.

body: All lanes of I-41/94 have reopened after a semi caught fire.
It happened Wednesday morning during rush hour at County G in Caledonia.
The fire forced a shutdown of the northbound lanes in the construction zone about 8 a.m.
Two southbound lanes were also closed, but have since reopened.
Witnesses told WISN 12 News the truck was fully engulfed in flames.
The northbound lanes reopened just after noon.
Investigators have not said what caused the semi to catch fire.
Firefighters said the driver was hauling rolls of paper.
The semi driver was not injured.
In the first six months of this year, there were more than 210 crashes in the same stretch of the construction zone on I-94.

title: in new yahoo news
body: As two weeks of televised impeachment hearings and wall-to-wall coverage came to a close, a new Yahoo News/YouGov poll showed that a majority of registered voters believe Donald Trump abused his powers as president of the United States. But the country remained divided over the question of whether he should be impeached as a result.
The poll was conducted Nov. 20 to Nov. 22. There were five days of televised House Intelligence Committee hearings, ending Thursday, Nov. 21.

When asked to say whether they believe Trump did or did not commit specific acts in connection with Ukraine — the subject of the House impeachment inquiry — 58 percent of registered voters said they believe the president “asked a foreign leader to investigate a political opponent”; 51 percent said they believe he “withheld military aid to Ukraine until they agreed to conduct the investigations he wanted”; and 51 percent said they believe he “abused his powers as president.” (Respondents were not asked about any other allegations against Trump.)

These results suggest that a majority of registered voters have been largely convinced by the case House Democrats are making in Washington: that Trump pressured Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky to investigate former Vice President Joe Biden and his son by using nearly $400 million in military assistance as a quid pro quo — and that he overstepped the bounds of the presidency in the process.

Yet only 48 percent of registered voters said they favor impeaching Trump or removing him from office — slightly more than the 45 percent who opposed impeaching or removing him, but less than a majority.

The remaining 7 percent were undecided whether Trump should be impeached or removed, a sign that some registered voters may still be persuadable. And while Republicans and Democrats have largely made up their minds about removal — 83 percent of Republicans oppose it; the same percentage of Democrats are in favor — independents are less certain: A slight plurality of them (40 percent) said Trump should be removed, while another 23 percent said they’re still not sure.

Americans are even divided by party over what they believe the likely outcome of the impeachment inquiry will be. Overall, only 11 percent believed that Trump will be removed from office; a plurality (41 percent) expected impeachment in the House followed by acquittal in the GOP-controlled Senate. That’s a view shared by a majority (54 percent) of Democrats. Yet a majority of Republicans (56 percent) believe that Trump won’t be impeached at all.

These disparities may reflect the fact that Republicans are paying less attention to the impeachment inquiry than Democrats. Fifty-six percent of Democrats said they have been following the congressional hearings “very closely” or “somewhat closely”; among Republicans, that number was 11 percentage points lower.

Regardless, Americans say impeachment will play a big role in how they vote in next November’s congressional elections. Asked to rate how important their current representative’s impeachment vote will be in their decision about casting their own vote for Congress, Democrats and Republicans were in rare agreement, with 74 percent in both parties saying it will be either “very important” or “somewhat important.”

The survey was conducted by YouGov for Yahoo News. A representative sample of 1,500 adults from YouGov’s research panel were interviewed online. The sample was weighted by age, race, gender, education, voter registration and 2016 presidential vote. The margin of error (MOE) for the full sample was 2.8 percent. The sample included 1,002 registered voters, and the MOE for percentages of registered voters is 3.4%.

title: i 35
body: A major section of interstate in Des Moines will close briefly Saturday night as work continues on an overhaul of a congested interchange.

From 10 p.m. Saturday until an undetermined time Sunday morning, Interstate Highway 35/80 will be closed to all traffic between the Douglas Avenue and 86th Street exits in Urbandale, the Iowa Department of Transportation said in a news release.
During the closure construction crews will install two of four girders for a new bridge over the closed section of road.
"The interstate will be reopened to traffic once the girders are secured and traffic can safely pass under them," IDOT said in a news release.

Two remaining girders will be installed during a similar closure in December. The $44 million project will add a flyover bridge linking I-35/80 to Iowa Highway 141 and new interchanges at Meredith Drive.

During the temporary closure Saturday night and Sunday morning, traffic is encouraged to use the U.S. 65/Iowa 5 bypass or Interstate 235, IDOT said. Local traffic will be able to use a detour on 86th street and Douglas Avenue through Urbandale.

title: top moments from the msnbc
how grappler aims to end police chases safely (w
body: His idea was a vehicular lasso to grab a perp's vehicle by the tire. A roofing contractor by trade, Stock was naturally handy and a proficient welder, so he began prototyping the concept on his own vehicle. He quickly confirmed his theory that a moving vehicle's spinning tire would indeed pull a loop of tow-strap material around itself if said strap could be forced into firm contact with it.

That prototype led to many iterations, all of them self-financed by Stock and his lucrative house-flipping business in the booming Phoenix metro area. His final Grappler design uses 2-inch nylon webbing with a 20,000-pound test strength; in many instances it's doubled for a 40,000-pound capacity.

The webbing forms a "ladder" net of sorts. The sides of the ladder are about 5 feet long and consist of doubled-up webbing with metal rings that connect to six 52-inch-wide "rungs." The front-most rung includes some pads to improve tire engagement in the rain.

The tether connecting the webbing to the police vehicle varies in length to suit the particular agency's needs and is accordion-stitched in such a way as to break away gradually as the vehicle is brought to a halt. The typical extended length of 30 to 40 feet starts out at 15 or fewer stitched feet. (The net must be replaced after each capture.)

How does the lasso reach the bad guy's car? At the press of a button in the police vehicle, two vertical bars hinge downward. Gas struts then fold open a second length of steel L-channel in each bar, pulling the net ladder out of its stowage cubby and into position. (Note that the Grappler, which weighs 180 pounds—similar to the strongest bull bars—works well as a push bar, though heavy bumps can compromise the deployment of the net.)

The police vehicle then drives up behind the suspect in a police chase, needing only 7 inches of ground clearance at the back of the vehicle, after which the contraption can ride down the bodywork to a lower clearance at the wheelhouse. A 5-mph closing speed is enough to engage the Grappler on a tire, then the net typically tangles and ties itself to the rear axle, stopping the wheel and often rendering the vehicle undrivable. You just roped that baddie, sheriff.

Even if the wheel isn't stopped, the police vehicle can typically brake it to a stop (unless the offending vehicle is much larger or heavier). The tether can be released at any point if the police wish to increase the distance to a hostile perpetrator or if the perp is heading over a cliff.

A Grappler arrest sometimes damages hydraulic brake lines, parking brake cables, ABS electronics wiring, brake backing plates, and other equipment around the rear wheel, but the taxpayers don't cover those costs. They also save the potentially vast expense of a badly ended car chase.
So far, the Grappler has been engineered to fit the
Chevy Tahoe
and all full-size pickup chassis. Stock prototyped a unit for a
Dodge Charger
pursuit vehicle, but the Charger's weight means it can't always stop a fleeing vehicle in a police chase, especially if the captured wheel doesn't lock, so he might not offer that fitment.

Installing a new Grappler costs $5,000, which includes officer training. Replacing a spent net runs $400. Units started shipping last November, and at press time 75 have been sold, though not all are deployed yet. Those in use have made 29 safe captures, only one of which included a bit of damage to the police vehicle. Grappler arrest videos may be boring, but they certainly won't keep you up at night.

title: tennessee education report card results reveal work ahead
body: At the end of October, the National Assessment of Educational Progress released 2019 results that measure the knowledge of nation’s fourth- and eighth-graders in math and reading at the national, state and district levels.
AAPL
STZ
TSLA
AMZN
We should certainly take a moment to celebrate the progress we’ve made, while remembering the work is far from done.

The Memphis Education Fund exists to be a strategic partner to the future of our city, county and state by fueling talent, teachers, schools and our community with the vital resources essential to build a sustainable educational community that provides every child with the highest quality of education possible.
The 2019 Nation’s Report Card results provide valuable perspective around how well we educate students compared to other states and cities in the nation.

And while I’m ecstatic to see that Tennessee is beginning to trend upward, the fact is that our current condition remains unacceptable and urges us to do more and better for our students with greater urgency.

Although Memphis students held the line and saw significant gains in math, our students still lagged far behind the state and rank us solidly in the bottom third as compared to 26 other large cities across the country.
It’s clear that we are headed in the right direction. However, we must do what it takes to deploy data-driven strategies that ensure each child is fully equipped to maximize their potential.

As it relates to the Memphis Education Fund, we will continue to work with our partners and community collaborators to ensure that the Memphis and Shelby County community is doing our part to build a future where each child has access to high quality educational programs.

To this end, I have directed our staff to dissect this report and host a collaborative summit with our partners to be held early in the coming year to ensure we are focusing on high-impact strategies to support administrators, school leaders and teachers.

When we think about the future Shelby County -- home to an urban school district with students from all types of backgrounds and diverse and unique learning needs — supporting policy and strategies focused on effectively educating every public-school student is paramount.
So let’s build on our momentum so all students have every opportunity for success!
Tennessee Education Report Card Results Reveal Work Ahead / Opinion

title: the play's the thing for lancaster actor
body: LANCASTER - Peter Murphy lives for the theater and loves doing his art in Lancaster.
Currently, the Peter Murphy Players put on performances in the Town Hall auditorium on a regular basis.

"The Lancaster Town Hall is one of the most beautiful spaces in our area of which I am aware, with a stage. Its architecture creates an atmosphere of such profound beauty and dignity that is very difficult to part with after a performance," he said.
Murphy has directed plays and musicals in Lancaster for over five years, and said he wouldn't go anywhere else.

"I love Lancaster - the history, architecture and beautiful old homes, and most of all the people," he said. "I believe we live in a town that truly cares. We are very fortunate to have so many kind-hearted, good-willed professionals working in authority in our town."

Murphy's family moved to Lancaster when he was little; when he grew up, he stayed. The acting bug bit him during a sixth grade production of "The Pirates of Penzance" at the Imago School in Maynard, continuing throughout high school at the Trivium School in Lancaster. He said his artistic education since has been from "awe-inspiring mentors" in the fields of music and drama.
Having directed over 30 productions, he has had a variety of major and minor roles as an actor as well.
"Acting and directing, alongside music, are my most natural forms of expression; art enables me to speak," he said.

Murphy said there is only one difficulty of working at the Town Hall auditorium "articulating clearly enough so our audience can understand. The hall's acoustics create a magnificent echo, which can be used to an advantage in certain cases, but requires us to learn to enunciate far more 'dramatically' than we would in other spaces."
Rehearsals occur three to four weeks prior to a show.
"This time frame tends to help us to create more 'alive' and spontaneous performances together," Murphy explained.
The next production is "Cyrano de Bergerac," with one show only on Saturday, Oct. 26, which is "a very important day in the story of the play."
Murphy said it is "an ode to lasting love and true friendship about letting go of judgment and seeing the hidden beauty within the human person, set to poetry."
The show begins at 7:30 p.m. and is free, although "donations are greatly appreciated" given Peter Murphy Players are privately funded.
"Our longing is to inspire our audiences through our art, creating each performance as beautiful as we possibly can," Murphy said of the Peter Murphy Players troupe.

He holds occasional acting classes for young people in Lancaster, generally in collaboration with the Friends of Thayer Memorial Library, and hopes to do so again soon. He is also the theater instructor for the upper grades at the Imago School in Maynard.

"Actors are everywhere - I think some of us have been acting our whole lives and perfecting our art without even knowing it," he said. "Theater is first and foremost an art for the actor, not the director."

He is also "focused on growing as an artist." As an actor, his biggest challenge "is to be truthful onstage and to play a character rather play an emotion for its own sake." With directing, it's "improvement in the realm of organizational skills."
For Murphy, drama is his life's work, and Lancaster is his stage.

"I believe that theater, when it is striving to create a work of art, can bring wonderful fulfillment to many people's lives, both on and off stage. I hope to continue producing theater in Lancaster for years to come."

title: miami hurricanes wr
body: At Miami Hurricanes practice on Tuesday, Manny Navarro of
reported according to Miami Athletics that RS sophomore WR/TE
Evidence Njoku
is no longer with the Canes Football program.
Can confirm through
#UM
that
@Evidence_Njoku
is no longer on the team
— Manny Navarro (@Manny_Navarro)
November 12, 2019
Manny Diaz confirmed this move after practice, and Njoku himself posted the below embedded tweet regarding his move to transfer:
pic.twitter.com/9j0fmqp9HT
— E83 (@Evidence_Njoku)
November 12, 2019
The younger brother of former Canes TE and 1st round
NFL Draft
Pick David, the younger Njoku struggled to carve a role for himself on Miami’s offense over the past few years. For his career, Njoku had 1 catch for 11 yards as a Hurricane.

Coming to Miami as a 3-star recruit, Evidence Njoku was known for his height — a solid 6’6” — and leaping ability. He was a standout at Wayne Hills (NJ) HS and figured to take a similar timeline to his brother who redshirted before becoming a top weapon for Miami’s offense. But, for Evidence, the development just wasn’t there.

Earlier in the 2019 season, the tall and lithely built Njoku followed his brother’s footsteps and switched from WR to TE. But, that position doesn’t really fit his built — David was a FREAK who is built like a bodybuilder — and it’s hard to imagine that that disconnect was not part of this decision to transfer.
Njoku is the 3rd player to elect to transfer out of Miami’s program this fall. He follows OL Cleveland Reed and WR
Brian Hightower
in departing the Canes roster.
We wish Evidence Njoku the best in his future endeavors.

title: why you shouldn't split parental responsibilities 50
body: Most parents probably expect a bunch of new duties when they have a baby. But that doesn’t help couples split up the duties of a parent. Some dads might think they have a lock on the
duties of a husband
, but even the men who want to be as fair as possible may not be getting enough done.  For instance, you knew you’d be rocking feeding and
changing diapers

. But according to a survey of millennial parents 95 percent of moms claimed to do more diaper changing than their significant other, while 75 percent of dads insisted they did. In the same survey, 80 percent of women said they’d be more
likely to change dirty diapers
than their significant other, while only 43 percent of men said the same. That doesn’t particularly bode well for splitting the duties of a parent equitably.

But when it comes to happiness, intimacy, and overall relationship satisfaction, who does more matters less than a clear understanding of who does what. So says couples therapist Laura Silverstein, clinical director and co-owner of
Main Line Counseling Partners
, with her husband — so you know she practices what she preaches.

Because humans can’t have nice things, the happiest moment of your life — the birth of a child — is also the moment you’re most likely to call Silverstein to save your relationship from crumbling. That’s because you both now have more work to do and less money to do it with, and are total zombies. “Sleep deprivation is how you torture people. It’s a big deal that everyone’s walking around exhausted,” Silverstein says. Simply put, couples with small kids very rarely avoid conflicts about the division of labor.

“Nobody is getting any sleep, there’s so much laundry, all those bottles need to be sterilized, and by the way, who’s rocking the baby to bed?” Diaper changing factors in there, too, because, as Silverstein notes, “Babies p*** a lot. You can quote me on that.” Thanks — wouldn’t want to be accused of stealing that highly original thought. Silverstein admits she and her husband struggled with the same challenges, but they got through it, and with her help, so will you.

Silverstein isn’t surprised by the survey’s results because people tend to see things from their own perspective and thus have a tough time believing anyone else could possibly be working as hard as they are. When couples arrive at her office, however, Silverstein finds that everyone — men and women alike — believes they’re doing more than they can capably sustain. Recognizing that everyone is at the end of their rope is the first step to overcoming conflicts about who’s doing more.

“You come home from work, you’re exhausted, you feel like you can’t go another day without a full night’s sleep, but yet again you have to wake up in the middle of the night. It’s hard not to feel resentment if you see somebody sleeping in bed next to you, but guess what? They’re gonna wake up in 3 hours, too.”

Constant competing leaves couples feeling lonely, disconnected, and dissatisfied, emotionally and physically. Walking that path leads either to “A high-conflict environment or a business relationship where you’re just going through the motions,” both of which sound like they ought to be the road less traveled.

Instead, Silverstein says, tackle your individual stresses together through collaboration and mutual support. “This new baby is amazing but also really difficult. We both want to be connected to the new life that’s joined our family but also be connected and stay sexual beings with one another. Let’s be in this soup together; you and me against the world.” The team-oriented approach leads to greater happiness and emotional intimacy, which leads to physical intimacy and, after a
pep talk
like that, multiple championships.

Silverstein affirms, “People have the greatest relationship satisfaction when they both have a clear understanding of the division of labor and household responsibilities. The deciding factor isn’t who does more but the clarity around whose job it is to do what.” So the fairest split isn’t always 50/50.

Silverstein literally gives couples a checklist of every household chore — 136 of them, to be exact — and has them tick off who does what currently and who’d do what ideally. The result can be like that survey: both people think they do everything. But it leads to a collaborative discussion and a clear, equitable plan about who will do what. “Usually, there’s a higher level of happiness once there’s been a discussion about it, while there’s actually less happy with a 50/50 split because it’s unusual for people to feel exactly the same about each chore,” Silverstein says. Which makes complete sense — if you prefer kitty litter to human waste, but for your partner, it’s vice versa, do that. Happy p**** for all!
The key is to have a clear, direct, and honest conversation in advance, at a mutually agreed upon time. Nobody feels collaborative when they’re wrist-deep in p** at 3:00 AM. Again.

Note that Silverstein isn’t simply saying it’s better to divide all the jobs than share some. Most likely, your diaper changing plan will look something like, “I’ll take 6:00 AM since I’m up getting ready for work and you can take midnight since you’re up watching cartoons.” Every situation is different, but if you have a direct conversation about mutually agreed upon expectations in advance, you’ll avoid having the chores, arguments, and dirty diapers pile up.

title: brightline
body: JUPITER
— Leaders from Brightline/Virgin Trains USA will be at the Jupiter Community Center on Monday to talk about the train service's planned expansion between West Palm Beach and Orlando.
The information session is scheduled to last from 6 to 8 p.m. and will address various aspects of expansion, including construction timeline, new stations and quiet zones, the town said.
Representatives will also discuss
the replacement of the Loxahatchee River rail bridge
that runs parallel to Alternate A1A.
Replacing everything above the 1925 bridge's supports will likely take 14-16 months from a still-to-be-determined start date, Virgin Trains USA media director Mike Hicks has said.

Plans and renderings will also be available for viewing Monday, according to the town. Members of the public are invited to attend and can ask the Brightline/Virgin Trains USA representatives about the project.
The event will take place in the community center auditorium at 200 Military Trail.

title: cnn10   11
latest civiqs
body: It was a tale of two polls as South Bend Mayor Pete Buttigieg experienced a major boost and Sen. Elizabeth Warren experienced a major slide, according to data in the latest Civiqs/Iowa State University poll conducted in November.
Buttigieg, who has seen a statewide surge in Iowa polls since September, topped the polls as 26 percent of likely-caucusgoers' first-choice for Democratic nominee.
Warren, who commandeered the top spot in the September and October polls, experienced a 10 percent dip to a second-place ranking at 19 percent.
Dave Peterson, Iowa State University political science professor and pollster, attributed Buttigieg's rise to a strong Iowa campaign strategy and months of positive press.

"First off, Buttigieg is running a great Iowa campaign. Any time there's a big event, his people show en masse. They're loud and organized and getting his name out," Peterson said. "It's also been a really great month of positive press for Buttigieg, with most Iowa voters getting positive feedback about him."

Peterson said the poll asks the same pool each month, tracking preferential trends for caucusgoers, and likened Warren's slide in the November polls to former Vice President Joe Biden's slide in the October polls.

In addition to Buttigieg and Warren's swap, polling third and fourth was Sen. Bernie Sanders and Biden at 18 percent and 12 percent, respectively, which has not changed since the last poll in October.
Of the top four — Buttigieg, Warren, Sanders and Biden — Warren saw a 35 percent exodus of her first-choice supporters from October polls to November polls, according to Peterson.

"The opposite is true for Warren, with scrutiny of the release of her Medicare for All funding proposal, which causes voters to re-think Warren," Peterson said. "A lot of the concerns is across the small ideological space of Democrats, who are looking for someone more 'at home' for them."
According to the data, those exiting voters either joined Buttigieg or Sanders.
"We see ideological shifts, the people who switched from Warren to Buttigieg are more moderate," Peterson said. "While those who switch from Warren to Sanders tend to be more liberal."

The online poll of 614 likely Democratic caucusgoers was conducted from Nov. 15-19, asking voters to name their first and second choices, and also list candidates they do not want to get the nomination.
While Buttigieg has seen a rise in Iowa, his national polling has stayed static at around 5 percent whereas Biden and Warren have the lead in most national to early-state polling.

A new name cracked the Civiqs polls' top-five, as Sen. Amy Klobuchar notched percent 5 percent favorability. However, Peterson noted a significant distance between the top four candidates and the rest of the field.

"Outside of that top four, there's not a lot of positive news for the rest of the field," Peterson said. "The gap between Biden (fourth in polling) and Klobuchar (fifth in polling) is bigger than the gap between Klobuchar and the last polling candidate at 19. So there are clear two tiers."
As for newcomers to the Democratic field, former New York City mayor and businessmen Michael Bloomberg, who announced a bid in November, polled at 10 percent unfavorability in the November polls.

"So one thing that really stood out to me in this poll is that no one wanted Bloomberg," Peterson said. "Bloomberg's negative seem quite high, and he made his first appearance on the (unfavorability) list at 10 percent, which is quite high."
In contrast, another November latecomer, former Boston governor Deval Patrick, received roughly 1 percent favorability, but was not a first or second choice candidate for those polled.
The survey has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.9 percent, with the next poll results expected in mid-December.

title: medical company claims they have discovered cure for hiv
body: PITTSBURGH (KDKA) — A Maryland pharmaceutical company believes it may have a potential cure for HIV/AIDS.
American Gene Technologies (AGT) filed a drug application with the Federal Drug Administration.
The company claims that in the nearly 1,000-page document to the FDA, lies the cure for HIV/AIDS.
The single dose drug has a simple purpose, to eradicate HIV once and for al.
The company expects to hear from the FDA before the end of the year.
If their application is approved, clinical trials could begin in January.
However it could still be several years before the drug gets final approval and goes to market.
